{"blocks":[{"key":"ddtke","text":"Human Embryonic Kidney (HEK293) cells are biosafety level 2 (BSL-2) and should be handled according to the CDC's Biosafety in Microbiological and Biomedical Laboratories (BMBL) guidelines. They are considered BSL-2 not because they are inherently hazardous or infectious, but because of their potential to be infected with pathogens and in turn infect their handlers. Due to the impossibility to regularly screen this cell like for every human pathogen, HEK293 cells should always be handled as potentially infectious. Other BSL-2 cell lines include those positive for Legionella pneumophila, HIV, and other disease-causing pathogens in humans. 

","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":42,"length":25},{"style":"bold","offset":454,"length":63},{"style":"italic","offset":569,"length":22}],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":113,"length":63}],"data":[]},{"key":"cg3hn","text":"Dispose of ALL waste that comes into contact with cells such as pipettes, gloves, and materials as biohazardous waste.

","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"d8fvo","text":"Bleach all direct cell waste thoroughly. In our lab, our vacuum line tube empties in to a sealed waste jug with bleach already added to the bottom of it, making up at least 10% of the total volume. This way, aspirated media and cells immediately come into contact with the bleach. Before disposing of glass pipettes, we aspirate a small amount of 10% bleach through to clean both the pipette and tubing, then dispose of the pipettes as biohazardous sharps.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"D91E71BBFDB4492DBD251D6F286F0689","url":"https://www.cdc.gov/biosafety/publications/bmbl5/index.htm"}}}}
